  "fullDescription": "Takamagahara (È´òÂ§©Âéü, 'Plain of High Heaven'), also read as Takama-no-hara or Takaamahara, is the celestial realm in Japanese mythology where the kami (gods) dwell. According to the Kojiki and Nihon Shoki, Takamagahara is the highest of the three realms of existence, floating above the earthly realm (Ashihara-no-Nakatsukuni) and separate from the underworld (Yomi). It is here that the primordial creation deities first appeared spontaneously: Ame-no-Minakanushi, Takamimusubi, and Kamimusubi. Takamagahara is ruled by Amaterasu, the sun goddess, who governs the heavenly kami. The realm is depicted as a mirror image of the earthly plane, complete with fields, rivers, and palaces. Sacred rice grows in the divine fields, tended by Amaterasu herself. From Takamagahara, the kami descend to interact with the earthly realm, most notably when Ninigi descended to become the ancestor of the Imperial line. The Heavenly Rock Cave (Ama-no-Iwato) is located in Takamagahara, where Amaterasu once hid. The realm represents the source of divine order, light, and blessing that flows down to the earthly world.",
